However, upon closer inspection of the Flags attribute '.A...F', I notice that it indicates a FIN flag was present. This suggests that an established connection (SYN-ACK) was closed by the sender using a FIN packet. In typical legitimate traffic, clients usually close connections with FIN packets after they have finished sending data to the server. However, this is also indicative of certain types of attacks.

Looking at other flows which include the .A...F flag, we can see that it's present in one "normal" flow and two "dos" flows. This could indicate potential issues. In particular, a high number of such flows may suggest a denial-of-service (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack.
